c diseases and institutional racism. Shocked by the high rate of preventable diseases in her patients, Boan realized that a paternalistic deficit model does not support Indigenous communities. Through working to provide medical services in Indigenous communities and learning firsthand from her Indigenous patients, Boan embarked on a road to enlightenment and reconciliation. In The Medicine Chest, Boan exposes the healthcare disparities in a country that prides itself on an equitable healthcare system and examines the devastating effects of diabetes, the myth of “the drunken Indian,” the inner workings of hospitals, Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls, epidemics on reserves, and residential school trauma. Exploring the intersectionality of common diseases and social determinants of health gained from her experience of caring for Indigenous patients, Boan weaves historical data, comments on health policy, and jurisdictional gaps into the narrative while investigating how Canada’s healthcare system is failing those most in need.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDiscrimination in medical carezCanada. 0aHealth services accessibilityzCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxHealth and hygienezCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxMedical carezCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh  aAhtahkakoop.  aCanada Health Act.  aCovid.  aDaystar First Nation.  aFederal-Provincial relations.  aFederalism.  aFirst Nation.  aGeorge Gordon First Nation.  aHIV.  aHepatitis C.  aJordan’s principle.  aKawacatoose First Nation.  aMMIWG.  aMetis.  aMuskewagan First Nation.  aNIHB.  aOCAP.  aRegina.  aSaskatchewan Health Authority.  aSaskatchewan.  aTRC.  aThe Indian Act.  aTouchwood Hills.  aTreat 4.  aTreaty 6.  aamputation.  acontinuity of care.  adeath and dying.  